{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17605633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17605633"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:04:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:04:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15872"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15872"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64705"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8563"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15872"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50139"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2203"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7061"},{"type":"tags","id":"7070"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20535"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20537"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21409"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64705"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to his general practitioner for a routine check-up. During examination, a small, soft, translucent swelling is noted immediately above and separate from the right testis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Causes significant testicular pain","Contains only serous fluid","Indicates malignant potential","Originates from dilated efferent ductules","Requires surgical removal"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a spermatocele. This is a relative common and often incidental finding. A spermatocele is a benign cystic accumulation of sperm-containing fluid that typically develops in the head of the epididymis. \u003Cstrong\u003ESpermatoceles arise from dilated efferent ductules\u003C/strong\u003E that connect the rete testis to the epididymis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cyst \u003Cstrong\u003Econtains serous fluid mixed with sperm\u003C/strong\u003E, not just serous fluid alone. Most spermatoceles are asymptomatic and \u003Cstrong\u003Edo not require surgical removal\u003C/strong\u003E unless they cause discomfort or cosmetic concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpermatoceles are typically painless and \u003Cstrong\u003Edo not cause significant testicular pain\u003C/strong\u003E. They are benign lesions and \u003Cstrong\u003Edo not indicate malignant potential\u003C/strong\u003E. They can be distinguished from other scrotal masses by their characteristic location above the testis and their translucent appearance when examined with a bright light (transillumination test).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A spermatocele is a benign, fluid-filled cyst in the epididymis containing sperm.","Spermatoceles are typically painless and often discovered incidentally.","Spermatoceles commonly arise from dilated efferent ductules of the epididymis."],"references":["Lundstr\u00f6m KJ, S\u00f6derstr\u00f6m L, Jernow H, Stattin P, Nordin P. Epidemiology of hydrocele and spermatocele; incidence, treatment and complications. Scand J Urol. 2019 Apr-Jun;53(2-3):134-138. doi: 10.1080/21681805.2019.1600582. Epub 2019 Apr 16. PMID: 30990342.","Walsh TJ, Seeger KT, Turek PJ. Spermatoceles in adults: when does size matter? Arch Androl. 2007 Nov-Dec;53(6):345-8. doi: 10.1080/01485010701730690. PMID: 18357964.","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50139"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15872"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50139"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T16:23:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T16:24:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8563"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64705"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","po